<li id="cite_note-27"><b><a href="#cite_ref-27" title="">^</a></b> Barsky (1997), <cite style="font-style:normal" class="web"><a href="http://cognet.mit.edu/library/books/chomsky/chomsky/4/17.html" class="external text" title="http://cognet.mit.edu/library/books/chomsky/chomsky/4/17.html" rel="nofollow">"Chapter 4"</a><span class="printonly">. <a href="http://cognet.mit.edu/library/books/chomsky/chomsky/4/17.html" class="external free" title="http://cognet.mit.edu/library/books/chomsky/chomsky/4/17.html" rel="nofollow">http://cognet.mit.edu/library/books/chomsky/chomsky/4/17.html</a></span><span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved on 2007-09-04</span>.</cite><span class="Z3988" title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.btitle=Chapter+4&amp;rft.atitle=&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fcognet.mit.edu%2Flibrary%2Fbooks%2Fchomsky%2Fchomsky%2F4%2F17.html&amp;rfr_id=info:sid/en.wikipedia.org:Noam_Chomsky"><span style="display: none;">&#160;</span></span> Barsky quotes an excerpt of <a href="/wiki/Edward_Herman" title="Edward Herman">Edward Herman</a> examining why "one of America's most well-known intellectuals and dissidents would be thus ignored and even ostracized by the mainstream press." For example, "Chomsky has never had an Op Ed column in the <i><a href="/wiki/Washington_Post" title="Washington Post" class="mw-redirect">Washington Post</a></i>, and his lone opinion piece in the <i><a href="/wiki/New_York_Times" title="New York Times" class="mw-redirect">New York Times</a></i> was not an original contribution but rather excerpts from testimony before the <a href="/wiki/Senate_Foreign_Relations_Committee" title="Senate Foreign Relations Committee" class="mw-redirect">Senate Foreign Relations Committee</a>."</li>
